DI setup\n2. The API tests for controller and gateway\n3. The design system widg
etbook\n4. The shared types\n5. The API contract sync script\n6. The database mi
gration\n\nLet me also look for specific issues:\n- In `im.service.ts` line 311,
the raw SQL query uses `WHERE conversation_id IN (?)`. With mysql2, passing `[co
nversationIds]` (an array) to a single `?` placeholder should expand it correctl
y to `IN (?, ?, ?)`. This is standard mysql2 behavior.\n- In `chat_page.dart`, t
he `ListView.builder` uses `reverse: false`. Since messages are loaded oldest-fi
rst (after the reverse in getMessages), new messages are appended at the end. Th
e scroll controller scrolls to bottom on new messages. This seems correct.\n- In
`im_bloc.dart`, `_onMessageReceived` auto-sends read receipt for the current con
versation, which is good.\n- In `im_bloc.dart`, `_messages.insertAll(0, result.i
tems)` for loading older messages - since result.items are in ascending order fr
om the API, and `_messages` is also in ascending order, inserting at position 0 
would put older messages before newer ones. But wait, `getMessages` returns item
s in ascending order, and when loading more with a cursor, it returns the next o
lder batch in ascending order. So inserting at position 0 is correct.\n- However
, looking at `getMessages` in `im.service.ts`: `qb.orderBy("m.sequence_id", "DES
C").take(limit + 1)`. Results come back DESC. Then `messages.reverse()` makes th
em ASC. The `nextCursor` is `messages[0].sequence_id` after reverse - which is t
he oldest sequence_id in the returned batch. But wait, if we\'re loading more ol
der messages, the cursor should be the oldest sequence_id so we can query `seque
nce_id < cursor`. That seems correct.\n\nWait, actually there\'s an issue in `ge
tMessages` nextCursor logic:\n```typescript\nconst nextCursor =\n  hasMore && me
ssages.length > 0 ? String(messages[0].sequence_id) : null;\n```\nAfter `message
s.reverse()`, `messages[0]` is the oldest message in the returned batch. So `nex
tCursor` is the oldest sequence_id. When loading more, the client sends this cur
sor, and the query does `m.sequence_id < :cursor`. This correctly gets messages 
with sequence_id less than the oldest message in the current batch. This is corr
ect for "load older" pagination.\n\nBut wait - what about the initial load? The 
initial load has no cursor, returns the newest messages in DESC order, keeps the
newest `limit` messages, reverses them to ASC. So `messages[0]` is the oldest of
the newest batch. When the user scrolls up, they want older messages, so `sequen
ce_id < oldest_of_newest` is correct. Yes, this works.\n\nLet me check if there 
are issues with the cursor for conversations:\n```typescript\nconst nextCursor =
