r the E2E user, so the E2E flow\'s dependency on pre-existing conversations is s
atisfied. Good.\n\nLet me also check if there\'s a potential issue with `Profile
CompletionGuard` being provided in both `MatchingModule` and `ImModule`. NestJS 
will create separate instances unless it\'s marked as `@Injectable({ scope: Scop
e.DEFAULT })` which is the default. Since it\'s just a guard class, having multi
ple instances is fine.\n\nOne more thing: Looking at the ` matching.service.ts` 
transaction in `checkAndCreateMutualMatch`:\n```typescript\nreturn this.dataSour
ce.transaction(async (manager) => {\n  try {\n    const match = manager.create(M
atchEntity, { ... });\n    await manager.save(MatchEntity, match);\n    const co
nversation = manager.create(ConversationEntity, { ... });\n    await manager.sav
e(ConversationEntity, conversation);\n    // ...\n  } catch (err) {\n    // hand
le duplicate\n  }\n});\n```\n\nThe duplicate handling inside the catch block doe
s:\n```typescript\nconst existing = await manager.findOne(MatchEntity, {\n  wher
e: { user_a_id: userA, user_b_id: userB },\n});\nif (existing) {\n  const conv =
await manager.findOne(ConversationEntity, {\n    where: { match_id: existing.id 
},\n  });\n  return { ... };\n}\n```\n\nBut this is inside a `catch` block of a 
transaction. If a duplicate error occurs, the transaction might already be marke
d for rollback by some database systems. However, with MySQL/InnoDB, a duplicate
key exception doesn\'t automatically rollback the transaction - it just aborts t
he current statement. So continuing within the same transaction should be fine. 
But this is a subtle point.\n\nActually, looking at TypeORM\'s `dataSource.trans
action`, if an error is thrown inside the callback and not caught, the transacti
on is rolled back. But here, the error IS caught inside the callback, so the cal
lback returns normally, and TypeORM will commit the transaction. However, if the
database has already aborted the statement due to the duplicate key, subsequent 
statements in the same transaction might behave differently depending on the DB.
\n\nIn MySQL, a duplicate key error sets an error state but doesn\'t abort the t
ransaction. You can continue. So this should be fine. Not an issue.\n\nLet me fi
nalize my review findings:\n\n## Blocking\n1. ChatPage scroll to bottom on ImMes
